+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Is it Time for an Open Source Certificate Authority?               |
|   from the definitely-time-for-ice-cream dept.                     |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Sunday April 29, @10:22 (Encryption)       |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/29/1255206           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]cagnol writes "So far there are three free ways to get a free
certificate to sign your e-mail and receive encrypted communications:
Thawte, Comodo and CAcert. [1]Thawte's root certificate is in mainstream
browsers. Thawte's interface is good and the web of trust allows for
increased security by verifying people's identity. However Thawte is not
open-source; worse: it is own by VeriSign. [2]Comodo's root certificate
is in mainstream browsers too but there is no web of trust and their
forms are not always working. [3]CAcert is the closest to an open-source
certificate authority but is not open-source and it seems that parts of
the system are shaky. CAcert provides a web of trust. Unfortunately,
CAcert's root certificate is not in mainstream browsers. Don't you think
it is time for a true open-source certificate authority? Should this
community be related to the Mozilla Foundation and comply, since day one,
with the requirements to get a root certificate in Firefox?"

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/29/1255206

Links:
    0. mailto:john@cagnol.net
    1. http://www.thawte.com/
    2. http://www.comodo.com/
    3. http://www.cacert.org/


